  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes around the world that address money laundering.  Here are some of the most important and common ones, focusing on the US and international frameworks:\n\n**United States:**\n\n*   **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970 (as amended by the Patriot Act of 2001 and other legislation):** This is the cornerstone of US anti-money laundering (AML) laws. It requires financial institutions to:\n\n    *   Maintain records and file reports that are determined to have a high degree of usefulness in criminal, tax, and regulatory matters.\n    *   Establish AML programs, including know-your-customer (KYC) procedures.\n    *   Report suspicious transactions (Suspicious Activity Reports or SARs).\n    *   Report cash transactions over \\$10,000 (Currency Transaction Reports or CTRs).\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This act made money laundering a federal crime for the first time. Key provisions include:\n\n    *   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments):**  Criminalizes financial transactions involving the proceeds of \"specified unlawful activity\" (SUA) with the intent to promote further criminal activity, conceal the nature/source/ownership of the proceeds, or evade taxes.  This statute is very broad and widely used.\n    *   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Specified Unlawful Activity):** Criminalizes knowingly engaging in monetary transactions of over \\$10,000 derived from specified unlawful activity.  Unlike \u00a7 1956, this doesn't require intent to conceal, but it has a higher threshold for the amount of money involved.\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:**  Enacted in response to the 9/11 attacks, this act significantly strengthened AML laws and expanded the scope of the BSA. Key provisions include:\n\n    *   Enhanced customer due diligence requirements for financial institutions.\n    *   Expanded the definition of \"financial institution\" to include a wider range of businesses.\n    *   Strengthened information sharing between law enforcement and financial institutions.\n    *   Addressed correspondent banking and shell banks.\n*   **Other Relevant Statutes:**  Depending on the specifics of the case, other federal statutes can be relevant, such as those related to tax evasion, wire fraud, mail fraud, and drug trafficking (as these are often \"specified unlawful activities\" that generate the illicit proceeds).\n\n**International:**\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a law themselves, the FATF Recommendations are the international standard for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.  Over 200 countries and jurisdictions have committed to implementing these recommendations.  They cover a wide range of topics, including:\n\n    *   AML/CFT (Counter-Terrorist Financing) policies and coordination.\n    *   Criminalization of money laundering and terrorist financing.\n    *   Customer due diligence and record-keeping.\n    *   Reporting suspicious transactions.\n    *   International cooperation.\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention):**  This UN treaty includes provisions related to money laundering, requiring signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds of crime.\n*   **European Union Directives on Anti-Money Laundering:** The EU has issued a series of directives on AML, which require EU member states to implement national laws to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. These directives are regularly updated to reflect evolving threats and international standards.\n*   **National Laws of Individual Countries:**  Virtually every country has its own national laws addressing money laundering.  These laws vary in their specifics, but they generally criminalize money laundering activities and require financial institutions to implement AML programs.\n\n**Key Concepts:**\n\n*   **Specified Unlawful Activity (SUA):** This is a crucial element in many money laundering statutes.  It refers to the underlying criminal activity that generates the illicit proceeds that are being laundered. The list of SUAs is often quite extensive and includes crimes like drug trafficking, fraud, bribery, corruption, and terrorism financing.\n*   **Know Your Customer (KYC):**  Financial institutions are required to verify the identity of their customers and understand the nature of their business relationships. This is a critical component of AML programs.\n*   **Suspicious Activity Report (SAR):** Financial institutions are required to report any suspicious transactions to law enforcement.\n*   **Currency Transaction Report (CTR):** Financial institutions are required to report cash transactions exceeding a certain threshold (typically \\$10,000 in the US).\n\n**In summary:**  Money laundering is addressed by a complex web of laws at the national and international levels.  The specific laws that apply in a given situation will depend on the jurisdiction and the specific facts of the case.  It's a highly regulated area, and financial institutions face significant compliance obligations.\n",
